Functionalizing Rasters from NEON

Megan Cattau

June 21, 2016

Objectives

Set the working directory and load packages

setwd("~/Documents/data/NEONDI-2016/Tues_pm_functional")
library(raster)
## Loading required package: sp
# library(rhdf5)
# library(rgdal)

Import a raster — A lidar canopy height model (CHM) and set values == 0 to NA (not trees)

chm <- raster("../NEONdata/D17-California/TEAK/2013/lidar/TEAK_lidarCHM.tif")

# assign chm values of 0 to NA
chm[chm==0] <- NA

Visualize histogram/density and plot vertical cutoff lines.

#inspect data
summary(chm)
##         TEAK_lidarCHM
## Min.     2.010000e+00
## 1st Qu.  9.139999e+00
## Median   1.631000e+01
## 3rd Qu.  2.375000e+01
## Max.     5.568000e+01
## NA's     2.133220e+05
# select thresholds 9 (1st qu) and 16 (Median)
density(chm)

hist(chm)
abline(v=c(9,16), col="red")

Classify the raster: <9m is generally grasses / understory, <16m small trees, and the rest are tall trees. A function could import the desired thresholds.

class.m <- c(0, 9, 1,
             9, 16, 2,
             16, 60, 3)
class.m
## [1]  0  9  1  9 16  2 16 60  3
# reshape the object into a matrix with columns and rows
rcl.m <- matrix(class.m, 
                ncol=3, 
                byrow=TRUE)
rcl.m
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    0    9    1
## [2,]    9   16    2
## [3,]   16   60    3
# reclassify the raster chm using the reclass function to create a new raster.
chm.classify <- reclassify(chm, 
                     rcl.m)

# look hist w function
hist(chm)
abline(v=rcl.m[,2], col="red")

pdf(file="TEAK_CHM_Density_w_breaks", width=6, height=7)
hist(chm)
abline(v=rcl.m[,2], col="red")
dev.off()
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 2

Plot it

# make room for a legend
par(xpd = FALSE, mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 4.5)) # xpd = FALSE means don't plot outside plot boundaries
# plot
plot(chm.classify,
     col=c("green","blue", "red"),
     main="Classified CHM",
     legend=F)
# allow legend to plot outside of bounds
par(xpd=TRUE)
# create the legend
legend.x<-par()$usr[2] + 20
                 # this is the second thing, which is the rightmost bond on x
legend.y<-par()$usr[4]+50-(abs(par()$usr[3]-par()$usr[4])/2)
legend(legend.x, legend.y,
       legend = c("Grasses / understory", "Short trees", "Tall trees"),  # make sure the order matches the colors, next
       fill = c("green", "blue", "red"),
       bty="n") # turn off border

par(xpd=FALSE)

Export Classified Raster

# export geotiff
writeRaster(chm.classify,
            filename="../outputs/TEAK/Classified_CHM.tif",
            format="GTiff",
            options="COMPRESS=LZW",
            overwrite = TRUE,
            NAflag = -9999)

Take the chm and create a hillshade (http://neon-workwithdata.github.io/neon-data-institute-2016/R/create-hillshade-R/) PLOT - layer the classified raster on top of the hillshade, add a legend for each “class” - legends are super tricky to simplifying this process with a function would be good. see: http://neon-workwithdata.github.io/neon-data-institute-2016/R/classify-by-threshold-R/ for my take on forcing a legend outside of the plot area using par settings. You may have other better forms of magic to make this work well. :) Export the plot figure to a pdf – publishable Export the classified raster as a geotiff with NaFlagg = -9999 to an outputs folder.
